articles.author: Maya Gebeily, Michelle Nichols
articles.description: The lightning overthrow of President Bashar al-Assad left Syrians, countries in the region and world powers nervous on Tuesday about what comes next as the rebel alliance took its first steps in a government transition.
articles.title: Syria's rebels work to form government, restore order after Assad ouster

articles.author: Julio-Cesar Chavez, Andrew Hay, Joseph Ax
articles.description: The man suspected of killing UnitedHealth executive Brian Thompson in a brazen shooting outside a Manhattan hotel was arrested and arraigned on gun and forgery charges on Monday, ending a massive five-day manhunt.
articles.title: Suspect in killing of UnitedHealth executive Brian Thompson in custody

articles.author: Timour Azhari
articles.description: The Sunni-led Islamist rebels who toppled Syria's Bashar al-Assad met elders in the former president's Alawite hometown on Monday and received their support, in what residents said was an encouraging sign of tolerance from the country's new rulers.
articles.title: Exclusive: In Assad's Alawite hometown, Syrian rebels win statement of support

articles.author: Maayan Lubell
articles.description: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel is set to take the stand on Tuesday for the first time in his long-running corruption trial under a court order that is likely to force him to juggle between the courtroom and war room for weeks.
articles.title: Netanyahu to take the stand in his corruption trial for the first time

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Taiwan's defence ministry reported a surge of Chinese military activity around the island on Tuesday, including 47 military aircraft, with Taiwan on high alert following the return of its president from a U.S. trip.
articles.title: Taiwan reports surge of Chinese military aircraft, ships operating nearby

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: South Korea's main opposition party said on Tuesday it would pass a government budget bill for 2025 that triggered President Yoon Suk Yeol's martial law decree last week, at a plenary session scheduled to be held later in the day.
articles.title: South Korea opposition party plans to pass government budget bill on Tuesday

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Ghana's electoral commission on Monday declared ex-president and main opposition leader John Dramani Mahama winner of Saturday's presidential election with 56.55% of the vote, according to provisional results.
articles.title: Ghana's ex-president Mahama wins presidential election with 56.55% of vote, electoral commission says

articles.author: Humeyra Pamuk
articles.description: The Biden administration is seeking ways to engage with Syrian rebel groups who ousted President Bashar al-Assad and is reaching out to partners in the region such as Turkey to help kick start informal diplomacy.
articles.title: US seeking ways to engage with Syrian rebel groups after Assad ouster

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos Jr said on Tuesday that the country will continue its resupply missions in the South China Sea without the need to deploy the navy, despite a recent incident with Chinese vessels.
articles.title: Philippines to continue resupply missions in S.China Sea, won't escalate situation

articles.author: Renju Jose
articles.description: A terror attack in New Zealand remains a "realistic possibility" over the next year as evolving global and domestic security trends continue to drive extremist sentiment, the country's intelligence service said on Tuesday.
articles.title: New Zealand spy agency says terror attack remains 'realistic possibility'
